			<h3 ><a href="#p166804">Re: Could I ask you a favor?</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="http://thejapanesepage.com/forum/viewtopic.php?p=166804&amp;sid=2c37a71ff2475bf541afb8231dbb699a#p166804"><img src="http://thejapanesepage.com/phpbb/styles/tjp-embed/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="http://thejapanesepage.com/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=85660&amp;sid=2c37a71ff2475bf541afb8231dbb699a" style="color: #00AA00;" class="username-coloured">becki_kanou</a></strong> &raquo; Sun 10.03.2010 10:08 pm </p>

			

			<div class="content">I thought that might be the reason. <br /><br />It seems that some perfectly good advice for writing: i.e. &quot;Don't OVERuse passives because they can make your writing sound limp&quot; has been reinterpreted as &quot;Don't use passives EVER!&quot;, which is just ridiculous. There are plenty of times when passives absolutely SHOULD be used.</div>

